  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Accessing OpenStreetMap Data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are a variety of publicly available geographic data sources which can\n",
    "be tapped to support various transportation service analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One popular resource is [OpenStreetMap](https://www.openstreetmap.org), which is a public, \n",
    "community supported geographic data service, which provides\n",
    "data on transportation infrastructure and a variety of other geographic data.  Much of\n",
    "this data can be accessed easily from Python using the open source OSMnx package, which\n",
    "loads data into GeoPandas and/or NetworkX formats."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import osmnx as ox\n",
    "import geopandas as gpd\n",
    "import networkx as nx\n",
    "import numpy as np"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Municipal Boundaries\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's get and display the boundary for Jupiter, Florida.  First we'll use the OSMnx package to pull this \n",
    "directly from the Open Street Map service, as a geopandas [GeoDataFrame](http://geopandas.org/reference.html#geodataframe).\n",
    "This type of data access is available as a one-line command."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "city = ox.geocode_to_gdf('Jupiter, Florida, USA')\n",
    "ax = city.plot()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "That's roughly the shape of the town.  We can compare against the town's own boundary file, which\n",
    "they conveniently publish online as well as a zipped shapefile."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "official_shp = tt.download_zipfile(\"http://www.jupiter.fl.us/DocumentCenter/View/10297\")\n",
    "city_official = gpd.read_file(official_shp)\n",
    "ax = city_official.plot()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Well that's pretty close, although they are a bit different.\n",
    "The data on open street map is commmunity maintained and the \n",
    "quality of the data is... uneven.  But it's free and portable,\n",
    "so may be useful for certain contexts.\n",
    "\n",
    "One important thing to notice is the axis labels-- the town's\n",
    "official boundary file uses a different coordinate system.  Whenever\n",
    "we want to use multiple geographic files together, they need\n",
    "to be using the same coordinate systems, otherwise the data will \n",
    "not align properly.  In the example below, the two plots of the \n",
    "town are in opposite corners of the map (and the red one in the\n",
    "lower left corner is too small to see at all)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = city_official.plot()\n",
    "ax = city.plot(ax=ax, edgecolor='red')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Fortunately, it's easy to\n",
    "check which coordinate reference system (*crs*) is used for each GeoDataFrame,\n",
    "by accessing the [crs](http://geopandas.org/projections.html#coordinate-reference-systems) attribute."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Geographic 2D CRS: EPSG:4326>\n",
       "Name: WGS 84\n",
       "Axis Info [ellipsoidal]:\n",
       "- Lat[north]: Geodetic latitude (degree)\n",
       "- Lon[east]: Geodetic longitude (degree)\n",
       "Area of Use:\n",
       "- name: World\n",
       "- bounds: (-180.0, -90.0, 180.0, 90.0)\n",
       "Datum: World Geodetic System 1984\n",
       "- Ellipsoid: WGS 84\n",
       "- Prime Meridian: Greenwich"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "city.crs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Projected CRS: PROJCS[\"NAD83(HARN) / Florida East (ftUS)\",GEOGCS[ ...>\n",
       "Name: NAD83(HARN) / Florida East (ftUS)\n",
       "Axis Info [cartesian]:\n",
       "- [east]: Easting (US survey foot)\n",
       "- [north]: Northing (US survey foot)\n",
       "Area of Use:\n",
       "- undefined\n",
       "Coordinate Operation:\n",
       "- name: unnamed\n",
       "- method: Transverse Mercator\n",
       "Datum: NAD83 (High Accuracy Reference Network)\n",
       "- Ellipsoid: GRS 1980\n",
       "- Prime Meridian: Greenwich"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 7,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "city_official.crs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Changing the crs for a GeoDataFrame is simple as well."
   ]
  },
  {

   "execution_count": 8,

   ]
  },

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Street Networks"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The OSMnx package can also download a street network.  We can do so again with\n",
    "a one line command, to get all the streets in Jupiter."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "jupiter_streets = ox.graph_from_place('Jupiter, Florida, USA')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Using the [plot_graph](https://osmnx.readthedocs.io/en/stable/osmnx.html#osmnx.plot.plot_graph) \n",
    "function from the OSMnx package, we can easily\n",
    "visualize the network we have downloaded."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x576 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = ox.plot_graph(jupiter_streets, show=False, close=False)\n",
    "ax = city.to_crs(epsg=4326).plot(ax=ax, edgecolor='red', facecolor=transparent)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You may notice that we have only received street segments fully contained with\n",
    "the reported municipal boundaries of the town.  Some important connectivity\n",
    "is lost, for example in the eastern section of town, which appears here as\n",
    "a peninsula, but in reality is not; Donald Ross Road, which marks the southern\n",
    "edge of town, actually continues east all the way to intersect with Ocean Drive.\n",
    "To capture this connectivity, we can instead define a study area that \n",
    "extends beyond the actual town boundaries.  Here, we'll add a buffer around\n",
    "the town of a few miles, to get a more complete street network."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "study_area = city.buffer(20000).envelope.to_crs(epsg=4326)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The size of the buffer is defined in units based on the coordinate\n",
    "system of the GeoDataFrame being buffered.  Since the city object\n",
    "has previously been set to use [EPSG:2881](https://epsg.io/2881),\n",
    "the units of the buffer are in feet.\n",
    "\n",
    "Given a defined study area, we can use a different OSMnx function\n",
    "to access the street network.  Using [graph_from_bbox](https://osmnx.readthedocs.io/en/stable/osmnx.html#osmnx.core.graph_from_bbox) \n",
    "allows us to download a rectangular area defined by latitude\n",
    "and longitude."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "west, south, east, north = study_area.total_bounds\n",
    "streets = ox.graph_from_bbox(north, south, east, west, simplify=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x576 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = ox.plot_graph(streets, show=False, close=False)\n",
    "ax = city.to_crs(epsg=4326).plot(ax=ax, edgecolor='red', facecolor=transparent, zorder=2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The resulting object we receive from either function is a \n",
    "[networkx.MultiDiGraph](https://networkx.github.io/documentation/networkx-1.10/reference/classes.multidigraph.html),\n",
    "which represents a directed graph with loops and parallel edges.  \n",
    "(Here, a \"graph\" is interpreted as in \"graph theory\", not as in \n",
    "a picture, although obviously we can create visualizations from\n",
    "the graph.)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "networkx.classes.multidigraph.MultiDiGraph"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 18,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "type(streets)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can inspect the nodes and edges of the graph seperately to get\n",
    "an understanding of how much street network we actually received."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(111027, 224740)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 19,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "len(streets.nodes), len(streets.edges)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Highway Types"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There is actually quite a bit of meta-data attached to the network as well.\n",
    "We can inspect data on any particular edge if we know the start and end\n",
    "nodes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'osmid': 202361740,\n",
       " 'oneway': True,\n",
       " 'lanes': '3',\n",
       " 'ref': 'FL 706',\n",
       " 'name': 'West Indiantown Road',\n",
       " 'highway': 'primary',\n",
       " 'maxspeed': '45 mph',\n",
       " 'length': 77.802}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 20,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "streets.edges[5379723376, 5379723385, 0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "More commonly, we'll want to analyze the network in a more aggregate fashion.\n",
    "As an example, we'll run tought all the links and tally up the total number of\n",
    "links with each of the unique 'highway' labels in the network."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'cycleway': 760,\n",
       " 'footway': 18600,\n",
       " 'motorway': 513,\n",
       " 'motorway_link': 691,\n",
       " 'path': 29774,\n",
       " 'primary': 1285,\n",
       " 'primary_link': 196,\n",
       " 'residential': 78168,\n",
       " 'secondary': 751,\n",
       " 'secondary_link': 44,\n",
       " 'service': 78576,\n",
       " 'steps': 32,\n",
       " 'tertiary': 7744,\n",
       " 'tertiary_link': 134,\n",
       " 'track': 6114,\n",
       " 'unclassified': 1358}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 21,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "highway_types = []\n",
    "for i in streets.edges.values():\n",
    "    highway_types.append(str(i['highway']))\n",
    "unique_highway_types, count_highway_types = np.unique(highway_types, return_counts=True)\n",
    "link_type_counts = {}\n",
    "for u, c in zip(unique_highway_types, count_highway_types):\n",
    "    link_type_counts[u] = c\n",
    "link_type_counts"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It's also possible to condense all that stuff into one line of python code:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'cycleway': 760,\n",
       " 'footway': 18600,\n",
       " 'motorway': 513,\n",
       " 'motorway_link': 691,\n",
       " 'path': 29774,\n",
       " 'primary': 1285,\n",
       " 'primary_link': 196,\n",
       " 'residential': 78168,\n",
       " 'secondary': 751,\n",
       " 'secondary_link': 44,\n",
       " 'service': 78576,\n",
       " 'steps': 32,\n",
       " 'tertiary': 7744,\n",
       " 'tertiary_link': 134,\n",
       " 'track': 6114,\n",
       " 'unclassified': 1358}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 22,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dict(zip(*np.unique([str(i['highway']) for i in streets.edges.values()], return_counts=True)))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# In April 2020, the data looked like this...\n",
    "# {'cycleway': 454,\n",
    "#  'footway': 8780,\n",
    "#  'motorway': 511,\n",
    "#  'motorway_link': 681,\n",
    "#  'path': 23524,\n",
    "#  'primary': 1871,\n",
    "#  'primary_link': 239,\n",
    "#  'residential': 67821,\n",
    "#  'secondary': 179,\n",
    "#  'service': 43658,\n",
    "#  'steps': 30,\n",
    "#  'tertiary': 6758,\n",
    "#  'tertiary_link': 123,\n",
    "#  'track': 5882,\n",
    "#  'unclassified': 1408}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Remove Minor Link Types\n",
    "\n",
    "As you can observe above, the OpenStreetMap network includes a whole lot of content, including \n",
    "(at least in Jupiter) a lot of pedestrian and minor links.  Let's abandon all these low level links."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 24,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "major_types = {\n",
    "    'motorway', 'motorway_link', \n",
    "    'primary', 'primary_link',\n",
    "    'secondary', 'secondary_link', \n",
    "    'tertiary', 'tertiary_link',\n",
    "}\n",
    "streets.remove_edges_from( [ \n",
    "    k for (k,v) in streets.edges.items() \n",
    "    if v.get('highway') not in major_types\n",
    "] )"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "(111027, 11358)"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 25,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "len(streets.nodes), len(streets.edges)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We've removed a large number of links, although so far all the nodes remain."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 26,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x576 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = ox.plot_graph(streets)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are a lot of leftover unconnected nodes -- when we dropped \n",
    "the footpaths and minor streets, we didn't drop footpath nodes.  Let's do that now."
   ]
  },
  {

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### Check for Unconnected Network Parts\n",
    "\n",
    "To check for network connectivity, we'll find shortest paths from one central node to all other nodes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 29,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "jupiter_center = 382641489 # Node at Northbound Old Dixie at Westbound Indiantown\n",
    "\n",
    "# Nodes that can be reached from jupiter_center\n",
    "connected_nodes_out = set(nx.shortest_path(streets, source=jupiter_center, weight='length').keys())\n",
    "\n",
    "# Nodes that can reach jupiter_center\n",
    "connected_nodes_in = set(nx.shortest_path(streets, target=jupiter_center, weight='length').keys())\n",
    "\n",
    "# Nodes that are full connected \n",
    "connected_nodes = connected_nodes_out & connected_nodes_in\n",
    "\n",
    "# The rest\n",
    "unconnected_nodes = [node for node in streets.nodes() if node not in connected_nodes]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's view a map of the unconnected nodes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x576 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "nc = ['w' if node in connected_nodes else 'r' for node in streets.nodes()]\n",
    "fig, ax = ox.plot_graph(streets, node_color=nc)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Looks like the unconnected nodes are mostly divided highways that enter or leave the study area.\n",
    "This makes sense, and in a complete demand model these would get external stations\n",
    "at the ends.  But let's just drop them for this example."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
